This list specifies allowable platforms (Google Sites/GitHub Pages) for job-seeking website submission. It defines valid technical solutions for the project, directly supporting the required structure and completeness criteria in the rubric. The platform choice impacts content organization and deployment methodology, serving as a foundational decision point for the website development process.

This list defines core components for job positioning in a personal career website, including a positioning statement and key skills/tags. It directly supports the 'Basic information and job positioning' rubric criterion (3 points) by establishing clear career identity and keyword alignment, which are essential for effective job-seeking website structure and visibility.

This list defines the 'About Me' section's content structure for a job-seeking website, specifying self-introduction, education details, and strengths. It ensures alignment with project requirements for personal branding, completeness, and skills alignment, directly supporting the rubric's focus on basic information and structural coherence.

This list categorizes technical, business, and tool-based skills for a job-seeking website, supporting the 'Skills' section's requirement to demonstrate capabilities and value creation. It aligns with rubric criteria for structure, skills alignment, and job positioning, providing essential information for knowledge retrieval about the candidate's competencies.

This list outlines the 'Projects (Portfolio)' section requirements for the job-seeking website, mandating two projects with detailed 'project card' information. It ensures alignment with the rubric's focus on skills demonstration and value creation, reinforcing the website's purpose as a professional portfolio. The structure supports the broader goal of presenting competencies through concrete examples.

This page introduces the job-seeking website project, specifying submission guidelines, mandatory sections, and rubric criteria. It establishes the structural foundation for the website, linking required sections to evaluation metrics like completeness and skills alignment. The content sets parameters for organizing content and ensuring alignment with assessment criteria, serving as a directive for the broader project execution.

This list defines the mandatory components for documenting projects in a job-seeking website portfolio. It emphasizes problem-solving context, data specifics, technical approaches, and measurable outcomes to align with the rubric's focus on project quality. The structure supports professional storytelling and skill alignment, directly contributing to the website's goal of showcasing technical expertise and value creation.

This list outlines resume submission methods for the job-seeking website project, specifying downloadable links or embedded sections. It ensures compliance with submission requirements and supports rubric criteria for completeness and professional presentation. The content directly relates to the 'Resume / CV' section mandate and enhances the website's effectiveness as a job-qualification showcase.

This list defines the contact information requirements for a job-seeking website, prioritizing email as a mandatory field while offering optional social media and phone number integration. It aligns with the project's focus on professional accessibility and supports the 'Contact' section mandate, ensuring clear communication channels for job seekers. The structure reflects submission guidelines and contributes to the website's overall functionality and credibility.

This list defines scoring criteria for evaluating job positioning in a personal career website (3 points). It establishes a tiered assessment of clarity in job targeting, headline effectiveness, and role-specific alignment, directly supporting the 'Home / Headline' section requirement and the broader rubric's focus on professional identity and audience relevance.

This list defines grading tiers for website structure, linking section completeness and navigation clarity to the 4-point rubric criterion. It specifies that 0–1 indicates missing sections and poor navigation, 2–3 shows partial compliance, and 4 represents full adherence to required sections with clear hierarchy. The list supports the broader project evaluation framework by quantifying structural quality expectations for job-seeking websites.

This list evaluates skills section quality in a job-seeking website, mapping skill organization to rubric points. It emphasizes alignment with job targets, structural evidence, and project linkage, directly supporting the 'Skills presentation and alignment' rubric category. The criteria guide creators to structure skills logically, ensuring they reflect capabilities and add value to the portfolio.

This page contains criteria for evaluating project descriptions in the job-seeking website project, focusing on clarity of value creation and skill alignment. It connects to the required 'Projects' section (Page 0) and the broader rubric (Page 2), emphasizing the 8-point weight assigned to project showcase quality. The content supports the project's goal of demonstrating technical capabilities through structured, impactful portfolio presentation.

This list defines scoring tiers for evaluating project descriptions in resumes/CVs, emphasizing progression from basic to advanced project narratives. It specifies requirements for completeness, detail, and impact demonstration, directly supporting the 8-point core rubric category. The structured criteria guide applicants to align their project presentations with assessment standards, ensuring clarity on value creation and skill alignment.

This list defines evaluation benchmarks for document formatting and accessibility, directly tied to the 'Project showcase quality' rubric section. It prioritizes clean layouts, functional links, and mobile compatibility, reflecting professional standards for digital communication. The criteria support the broader assessment of technical execution and value creation in project submissions, ensuring alignment with submission requirements and rubric objectives.

This list specifies mandatory fields for a professional document submission, focusing on author identification and digital accessibility. It directly supports the 'Basic information and job positioning' rubric category (3 points) by providing structured, actionable data required for professional presentation and evaluability. The items align with submission requirements and contextualize the broader emphasis on clarity and value creation in project descriptions.

Page 3 corresponds to the 'Project showcase quality' rubric section (8/20 points), containing detailed descriptions of projects that demonstrate skills, accomplishments, and value creation. It supports the submission requirements by providing concrete examples for skills alignment (3), structure (2), and professional presentation (5), while adhering to the directive that project descriptions must explicitly communicate actions taken, capabilities demonstrated, and measurable outcomes achieved.
